","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","about 1228":"circa 1228","1453":"1453","about 1269":"circa 1269","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Prideaux Place, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Polruan, Cornwall, England":"Polruan, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1228–":"about 1228–Deceased","1228–Female":"1228–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1248–Male":"1248–Deceased","1205–1251":"1205–1251","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","about 1228":"about 1228","1453":"1453","about 1269":"about 1269","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Prideaux Place, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Polruan, Cornwall, England":"Polruan, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cardinan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Adelard, Alberic, Clovis, Colette, Fabienne, Fernand, Francois, Germaine, Gilles.","French and English: from Old French, Middle English <i>cardinal</i> ‘cardinal’, the church dignitary (Latin <i>cardinalis</i>, originally an adjective meaning ‘crucial’). The surname was probably bestowed as a nickname on someone who habitually dressed in red, or who had played the part of a cardinal in a pageant, or who acted in a lordly and patronizing manner.","English: possibly also an altered form of   Carbonell  . Reaney notes that Cardinal's Farm in Foxearth (Essex) is recorded as <i>Carbonels</i> in 1381 and <i>Cardynals</i> in 1577."],"variants":[{"name":"Cardenal","meanings":["Spanish: from <i>cardenal</i> ‘cardinal’ (see   Cardinal  )."]},{"name":"Carbonell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Jorge, Jose, Juan, Eduardo, Rafael, Roberto, Carlos, Manuel, Miguel, Pablo, Rolando.","Catalan: from an old personal name, <i>Carbonellus</i> in Latin, derived from Latin <i>carbo</i> ‘coal, charcoal’. This surname is also found in southern France (mainly Pyrénées-Orientales).","English (of Norman or Huguenot origin): nickname for a man with dark hair or a swarthy complexion, from a diminutive of Anglo-Norman French <i>carbon</i> ‘charcoal’. The name was also reintroduced to Britain by Huguenot refugees in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Cardinale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Mario, Rocco, Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Cosimo, Salvador, Carlo, Cosmo, Francesca, Gasper, Gennaro, Angelina, Demetrio, Gaspar, Gerardo, Julio, Lucrecia, Romero, Rosario.","Italian: from <i>cardinale</i> ‘cardinal’ (see   Cardinal  ), a nickname for a haughty individual, or a metonymic occupational name for the servant of a cardinal."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":31,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":62,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":87,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":100,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":109,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Cardinan was born about 1228, in Devon, England, her father, Robert de Cardinham, was 25 and her mother, Emma de Prideaux, was 39. She had at least 1 son with Odo De Treverbyn. She lived in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom in 1268. She died in Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1228–":"umbes 1228–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1248–M